353
00:21:07,230 --> 00:21:12,270
And just to illustrate
how that happened

354
00:21:12,270 --> 00:21:16,950
or the consequence of that,
I will speak about a subject

355
00:21:16,950 --> 00:21:21,610
that appeared in 2000, and that
is with the genome sequence.

356
00:21:21,610 --> 00:21:24,450
In previous science,
it was recognized

357
00:21:24,450 --> 00:21:29,010
that our cells encode another
500 or more genes that we

358
00:21:29,010 --> 00:21:32,500
didn't know about, that
encoded small RNAs.

359
00:21:32,500 --> 00:21:35,710
These small RNAs were
called microRNAs.

360
00:21:35,710 --> 00:21:37,560
The initial discovery
of the first

361
00:21:37,560 --> 00:21:44,610
was in 1993 out of Gary Ruvkun
and Victor Ambros' [INAUDIBLE]

362
00:21:44,610 --> 00:21:45,700
network.

363
00:21:45,700 --> 00:21:49,020
It was done initially
with collaboration

364
00:21:49,020 --> 00:21:50,890
in Bob [INAUDIBLE] lab.

365
00:21:50,890 --> 00:21:55,870
And out of that came this
discovery of microRNAs.

366
00:21:55,870 --> 00:22:00,300
And as you will note, that was
recognized by a Nobel Prize

367
00:22:00,300 --> 00:22:03,810
in this year, 2024.

368
00:22:03,810 --> 00:22:07,780
This microRNA pathway is
present in every cell.

369
00:22:07,780 --> 00:22:14,200
It was totally unrecognized
until the 2000s by David Bartel

370
00:22:14,200 --> 00:22:15,080
and others.

371
00:22:15,080 --> 00:22:18,950
And it has become a major
regulatory-- involved in cancer,

372
00:22:18,950 --> 00:22:21,100
involved in many processes.

373
00:22:21,100 --> 00:22:24,830
And then at the
same time, in 1998,

374
00:22:24,830 --> 00:22:29,140
there was a discovery by Fire
and Mello of the fact that

375
00:22:29,140 --> 00:22:30,610
double-strand RNA--

376
00:22:30,610 --> 00:22:32,960
most RNA is single
stranded in the cell.

377
00:22:32,960 --> 00:22:35,050
But you can see double strand.

378
00:22:35,050 --> 00:22:37,780
And double-strand
RNA from a gene

379
00:22:37,780 --> 00:22:42,020
will silence the expression of
that gene in many organisms.

380
00:22:42,020 --> 00:22:44,840
Their work was done in
the worm C. elegans,

381
00:22:44,840 --> 00:22:48,910
but it was soon recognized
that that work interdigitated

382
00:22:48,910 --> 00:22:50,900
with the microRNA work.

383
00:22:50,900 --> 00:22:53,350
And this led us to
an understanding

384
00:22:53,350 --> 00:22:55,870
that there was another
biochemical system

385
00:22:55,870 --> 00:22:57,740
in the cell we didn't know.

386
00:22:57,740 --> 00:23:01,540
Andy Fire was a grad
student here at MIT,

387
00:23:01,540 --> 00:23:05,020
but did the work
after he left MIT.

388
00:23:05,020 --> 00:23:09,610
Using that work, and with
David Bartel and Phil Zamore

389
00:23:09,610 --> 00:23:13,480
and Tom Tuschl, postdocs, and
Paul Schimmel's influence,

390
00:23:13,480 --> 00:23:18,850
it became recognized
that this whole process

391
00:23:18,850 --> 00:23:22,030
of silencing a gene
with RNA offered

392
00:23:22,030 --> 00:23:25,140
a new therapeutic modality.

393
00:23:25,140 --> 00:23:32,610
We could use the natural pathway
in the cell, design a drug--

394
00:23:32,610 --> 00:23:36,150
siRNA-- from the
sequence, and then

395
00:23:36,150 --> 00:23:40,920
treat a patient if the
modulation of that gene

396
00:23:40,920 --> 00:23:42,660
would have an impact.

397
00:23:42,660 --> 00:23:48,720
So that was just another way of
possibly benefiting patients.

398
00:23:48,720 --> 00:23:53,310
And that led to then the
establishment of Alnylam,

399
00:23:53,310 --> 00:23:57,480
and the confrontation
that the big problem here

400
00:23:57,480 --> 00:24:00,270
was delivery of the RNA.

401
00:24:00,270 --> 00:24:05,680
We turned to engineers and other
chemists to solve that problem.

402
00:24:05,680 --> 00:24:08,550
Delivery of RNA into
cells is difficult

403
00:24:08,550 --> 00:24:11,430
because RNA is hydrophilic
and your cell has

404
00:24:11,430 --> 00:24:13,500
a membrane that's hydrophobic.

405
00:24:13,500 --> 00:24:18,430
And therefore you have to
transport the RNA into the cell.

406
00:24:18,430 --> 00:24:24,390
But once it's in the cell, it
will enter the microRNA pathway

407
00:24:24,390 --> 00:24:27,870
and carry out-- if it's
complementary to the messenger

408
00:24:27,870 --> 00:24:28,780
RNA--

409
00:24:28,780 --> 00:24:34,360
destruction of the messenger
RNA and then be catalytic.

410
00:24:34,360 --> 00:24:36,870
So the big issue
here was, could you

411
00:24:36,870 --> 00:24:40,750
introduce this RNA into cells?

412
00:24:40,750 --> 00:24:45,830
And that led to the development
of lipid nanoparticles, which

413
00:24:45,830 --> 00:24:47,530
look like a virus.

414
00:24:47,530 --> 00:24:51,330
They have a cationic
lipid of a certain type.

415
00:24:51,330 --> 00:24:54,200
Pieter Cullis taught us--

416
00:24:54,200 --> 00:24:58,300
that is a Canadian scientist
who made major contributions

417
00:24:58,300 --> 00:24:58,990
to this.

418
00:24:58,990 --> 00:25:02,350
Impacting the RNA into
these nanoparticles

419
00:25:02,350 --> 00:25:08,590
would, with the right ionic
pH and PK, give you then

420
00:25:08,590 --> 00:25:11,870
a change in conformation
of those lipids

421
00:25:11,870 --> 00:25:15,130
as the particle enters the cell.

422
00:25:15,130 --> 00:25:19,090
In your blood system,
you have a pH of seven.

423
00:25:19,090 --> 00:25:23,050
In the cell, it's nearly a
pH of 5 in this endosome.

424
00:25:23,050 --> 00:25:27,020
And that creates
this transition.

425
00:25:27,020 --> 00:25:30,700
That same technology--
similar technology

426
00:25:30,700 --> 00:25:33,430
was used in the
vaccination in COVID that

427
00:25:33,430 --> 00:25:35,710
rescued us from the pandemic.

428
00:25:35,710 --> 00:25:40,180
It has then been used to
treat billions of patients.

